            <mixed-citation id="d2244e204" publication-type="book">
Yoder traces Whitman, Williams, Pound, and
Hart Crane to the early Emerson, and Dickinson, Stephen Crane, Frost,
Stevens, and Ammons to the late Emerson (pp. 191-92)<fpage>191</fpage>
            </mixed-citation>
            <mixed-citation id="d2244e219" publication-type="book">
Porter
regards Emerson's poetic forms as rigid and restrictive, he ardues that the
essays' "broad reconciliation of art and reality foreshadowed the later
formal undertakings of Eliot and Pound, Crane, Olson and Williams, Stev-
ens, Lowell, and others" (p. 5)<fpage>5</fpage>
            </mixed-citation>
            <mixed-citation id="d2244e241" publication-type="book">
Bloom finds the dialectic between "Bac-
chus" and "Merlin," between "the assertion of the imagination's autonomy,
and a shrewd skepticism of any phenomenon reaching too far into the
undonditioned" (p. 292)<fpage>292</fpage>
            </mixed-citation>
            <mixed-citation id="d2244e259" publication-type="partial">
Robinson and Frost are exceptions: they "stem
from the later, resigned Emerson" (p. 292)</mixed-citation>
